flowRoot.flowPara: Assign probability to every possible clustering of data seen so far
e.g. Feldman, Griffiths, & Morgan (2009)
Pros
Principled: based on statistical inference
Flexible: extend naturally to hierarchical/joint learning
Cons
Not psychologically plausible: unconstrained in time/memory/processing
Often batch algorithms (require all data at once)
Computationally intensive to fit (full inference)
Specify representations and algorithms that operate on them
e.g. McMurray, Aslin, & Toscano (2009)
Pros
Direct mapping between model operation and cognitive processes
Generally include resource limitations
Cons

Harder to reason about how multiple models might work together across processes (e.g. phonetic and lexical learning)

flowRoot.flowPara: Online inference in a Bayesian non-parametric model using finite resources
Particle filter:
Each particle represents one hypothetical clustering of data points seen so far
Particles are updated in parallel when a new data point comes in.
Each particle chooses a cluster assignment based on:
The prior probability (more probability for clusters with many data points)
The likelihood of the new data point given the other points in that cluster (prefer compact clusters where points are similar)
Particles only need to keep track of sufficient statistics of each cluster (number, mean, and variance)
Can approximate Bayesian clustering online with finite resources
Bridge between computational- and algorithmic-level models of language acquisition.
Interpretation of output is tricky
Inference leads to uncertainty about number of clusters
To be useful clusters have to make contact with categories (words etc.).
Joint inference might help: context provides information about which clusters are categories (Feldman et al. 2013)
